Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA)¶


An autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) model is a generalization of an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model. ARIMA models are applied in some cases where data show evidence of non-stationarity, where an initial differencing step (corresponding to the "integrated" part of the model) can be applied one or more times to eliminate the non-stationarity.
Non-seasonal ARIMA models are generally denoted ARIMA(p,d,q) where parameters p, d, and q are non-negative integers, p is the order (number of time lags) of the autoregressive model, d is the degree of differencing (the number of times the data have had past values subtracted), and q is the order of the moving-average model.
ARIMA models can be estimated following the BoxJenkins approach:

  • test the hypothesis of the stationarity of the series
  • if alternative hypothesis is True ⇒ make a stationary series and find degree of differencing (d - the number of times the data have had past values subtracted)
  • study ACF (autocorrelation function) and PACF (partial autocorrelation), choose order of 'p' in the model of AR and order of 'q' in the model of MA
  • build model ARIMA
  • check model quality

Methods for smoothing values and Differencing to Remove Trends¶

In [5]:
ts_log = np.log(ts) # log-transform
ts_log_diff = ts_log - ts_log.shift()
ts_log_diff.dropna(inplace=True)

moving_avg = ts_log.rolling(14).mean() # moving mean
ts_log_moving_avg_diff = ts_log - moving_avg
ts_log_moving_avg_diff.dropna(inplace=True)
In [6]:
# plot autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation
def plot_acf_pacf(timeseries):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(211)
    fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf(timeseries, lags=40, ax=ax1)
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
    fig = sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf(timeseries, lags=40, ax=ax2)
In [7]:

Dickey—Fuller test¶

In [9]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

def test_stationarity(timeseries):
    
    # Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(7).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(7).std()
    
    # Plot rolling statistics
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 15))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax1.plot(timeseries, color='blue', label='Oridinal')
    ax1.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    ax1.plot(rolstd, color='black', label='Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.show()
    
    # Perform Dickey-Fuller Test
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    return 'Results of Dickey-Fuller Test: p-value = ' + str(dftest[1])
In [10]:
# it's obviously: ts isn't stationary
test_stationarity(ts)
Out[10]:

'Results of Dickey-Fuller Test: p-value = 2.9916188137978794e-15'
Conclusion: We can consider all of the converted series because they are stationary (except ts_log).¶

Estimation of Seasonality¶

In [14]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

def estimation_seasonality(avg_diff):
    decomposition = seasonal_decompose(avg_diff, freq=7)

    trend = decomposition.trend # trend
    seasonal = decomposition.seasonal # seasonal
    residual = decomposition.resid # residual

    fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 2))
    ax1 = fig1.add_subplot(111)
    ax1.plot(avg_diff, label='Original')
    plt.legend(loc='best')

    fig2 = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 2))
    ax2 = fig2.add_subplot(111)
    ax2.plot(trend, label='Trend')
    plt.legend(loc='best')

    fig3 = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 2))
    ax3 = fig3.add_subplot(111)
    ax3.plot(seasonal, label='Seasonality')
    plt.legend(loc='best')

    fig4 = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 2))
    ax4 = fig4.add_subplot(111)
    ax4.plot(residual, label='Residuals')
    plt.legend(loc='best')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # The residual of the idea must be stationary, we can test it:
    result = residual
    result.dropna(inplace=True)
    
    return test_stationarity(result)

Selection of the parameters p and q¶

The AIC measures how well a model fits the data while taking into account the overall complexity of the model.¶
In [18]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_model import ARIMA
import warnings

warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") # specify to ignore warning messages

result_aic = list()

ps = qs = range(0, 5)

for p in ps:
    for q in qs:
        try:
            model = ARIMA(ts_log, order=(p, 1, q))
            model_fit = model.fit(disp=0)
            result_aic.append([p, q, model_fit.aic])
        except ValueError:
            continue

Choosing the best model¶

In [19]:
best_aic = result_aic[0][2]
best_param = list()
best_model = result_aic[0]

for i in range(1, len(result_aic)):
    if best_aic > result_aic[i][2]:
        best_aic = result_aic[i][2]
        best_param = [result_aic[i][0], result_aic[i][1]]
        best_model = result_aic[i]

print(best_model)
